The paper deals with submodular optimization, which is a topic in both theoretical computer science (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG). The use of adaptive complexity as a measure of algorithm efficiency suggests that the paper may also be relevant to information theory (cs.IT). The analysis of the number of rounds required for achieving a certain approximation factor is a topic in computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper's focus on optimization suggests that it may also be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
